INSERT INTO `page_parts` (`id`,`name`,`filter_id`,`content`,`page_id`) VALUES ('40','excerpt','Textile','One would assume that no one would buy a bed specifically for sex, or that Bitch Kitty Racing readers limit their sexual activities to the bedroom.  Certainly not.  That\'s why they invented the kitchen table.','23');
INSERT INTO `page_parts` (`id`,`name`,`filter_id`,`content`,`page_id`) VALUES ('41','body','Textile','The date engineers here at Bitch Kitty Racing have discovered, through much scientific diligence, a furniture marker in singles which clearly indicates the owners\' compatibility.\r\n\r\n!/img/134.jpg!\r\n\r\nAnthropology indicates that men and women are different.  The sexes have different communications styles, emotional responses, remembrance of pain, etc.  While no sweeping generality is scientifically sound, general trends can nonetheless be valid.  It would never be correct to say that: All men just want sex,\" or: All women just want babies,\" when the reproductive success of the species depends on procreation, yet current theory indicates trends in mating habits specific to the sexes.  For additional information on this subject, please see \"Dutch Treat and Mate Selection.\":http://bitchkittyracing.com/articles/dutch-treat-and-mate-selection\r\n\r\nSo it is with couches and beds.  While neither sex will always have a specific piece of furniture of a specific quality, on several research outings our staff has noticed that women generally have better beds than do men, and that men generally have better couches than do women.  Better, of course, being a relative term, but here meaning more comfortable and suited to the purpose for which the object was created.  \r\n\r\nLet\'s start with the bed, shall we?  The bed purportedly has a single purpose: to forward sleep, yet everyone knows that a large majority of sex takes place in the bed, though one would assume that no one would buy a bed specifically for this purpose, or that Bitch Kitty Racing readers limit their sexual activities to the bedroom.  \r\n\r\nCertainly not.  That\'s why they invented the kitchen table.\r\n\r\nResearch shows that women\'s beds are superlatively comfortable places, resplendent in pillow tops, feather beds, extra pillows, linens selected on high thread count, and thick down comforters.  Men\'s beds tend to be more pragmatic, things like hard twin-sized mattresses with wool blankets, futons, piles of broken cinder blocks, floors, or perhaps the hallway by the front door. \r\n\r\n!/img/187.jpg!\r\n\r\nCouches show a reversal of the trend, which can easily be spotted while shopping for said pieces of furniture.  When men shop for a couch by themselves, they are invited to lie down on it to make sure it fits, the assumption being that there will be a lot of lying down taking place on the couch.  The salesperson knows that all important aspects of the male home life take place here: sports, beer, and sex.  The couch is not only the main place to watch _les 24 Heures du Mans_  on _le tlviseur_ while drinking _la bire_, it is also the place where all men know that any chance of intercourse begins if she comes back to his place.  This is the make-out function of the couch, and we\'ll come back to it.\r\n\r\nWhen woman shops for a couch she is asked about her dcor and presented with a different set of options other than just size, like fabric and color.  She is selecting a couch on form, while the male of the species selects a couch on function.\r\n\r\nSo while the male of the species will walk out having purchased an eighteen-foot black leather sectional, both functional and masculine, the female will leave the store with something that can\'t properly be called a couch at all, like a loveseat, divan, or futon sofa (as an aside, it is interesting to note here that the myth of the male being more visually acute than the female is dispelled.  No one could possibly think an eighteen-foot black leather sectional looks good).\r\n\r\nThis is where the make-out angle comes into play and its derivative, the subconscious desire to reproduce, i.e. settle down, is brought into light.  \r\n\r\nThe male couch has excellent make-out functionality.  It\'s large, spacious, and can easily accommodate two in a variety of positions, assuming it isn\'t actually leather off which the occupants would comedically slide (tactilely, leather is also the second unsexiest material on the list of unsexy materials on which to place the naked, heated human skin; it\'s too sticky, and becomes slimy and cold when wet.  Vinyl is, of course, the worst).  All sorts of sexual activity can take place on the male couch, from foreplay to intercourse.\r\n\r\nHowever, the couch is not really designed for sleeping.  Once playtime is over, it\'s also closer to the door.  \r\n\r\nMaking out on her couch is a different experience all together.  The divan has no back so the occupants fall off.  The loveseat is too small to allow freedom of movement.  The futon sofa has a cant to it that crushes both occupants to the inside.  Making out properly is nearly impossible on these devices, so the lovers wind up on the floor in self defense.  \r\n\r\n<txp:upm_image type=\"image\" image_id=\"188\" class=\"image\" />\r\n\r\nHey,\" she finally says.  This floor is really hard.  Why don\'t we hop into my superlatively comfortable bed?\"  There is a deeper intensity of feeling in the bedroom, of intimacy.  He knows that an invitation to the bedroom is very close to an invitation to spend the night.  Animally, it\'s like an invitation to nest, and the more comfortable the nest, the more likely the occupants will stay there.  \r\n\r\nOf course, this is only a general trend, yet it is in line with our ancient apelike bioanthropology.  The female of the species nested; the male of the species liked to visit nests.\r\n\r\nHowever, our sapient human behavior is different than out instinctual ape behavior, though perhaps just as subconsciously acted upon.  Let us remove what seem to be stereotypical generalities and reconsider the couch/bed tags.\r\n\r\nAn invitation to a comfortable bed is an invitation to sleep in it and, with regards to mating, an invitation to nest.  An invitation to a nice make-out couch is an invitation only to fuck.  \r\n\r\n!/img/133.jpg!\r\n\r\nBoth sexes may have nice couches and nice beds, or perhaps only one of each, or perhaps neither.  Yet the tags remain clear.  The eighteen foot black leather sectional brings to mind imagery of a person that likes stewies, Burt Bacharach, red meat, and Scotch.  The cosseting bed brings to mind imagery of Sundays spent in it reading the paper, falling asleep on a shoulder, cuddling, and children leaping on it in excitement for a trip to the zoo.  In this case, the couch sounds like a swinger and the bed sounds like a parent.  \r\n\r\nWinding up at your date\'s place is now a research outing, instead of winding up there because you\'re slutty.  Look at your own furniture before you go out.  By matching your date\'s make-out location preference to your own you stand a much better chance of finding an appropriate partner, whatever your preference.\r\n\r\n\r\n<script src=\"http://www.google-analytics.com/urchin.js\" type=\"text/javascript\">\r\n</script>\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\">\r\n_uacct = \"UA-1192760-1\";\r\nurchinTracker();\r\n</script>','23');
INSERT INTO `page_parts` (`id`,`name`,`filter_id`,`content`,`page_id`) VALUES ('42','excerpt','Textile','I didn\'t know if the cat would taste good if he died when he was this ill.  I keep an extra large stewpot around for the day that one of us finally succeeds in killing the other.  If I win, it\'s _Chat au Vin._  If he wins, I\'m sure I\'m _Homme Bourguignon,_ if he even bothers to cook me.  I imagine I\'ll just wake up one night to the sight of him thrashing around the bed, gulping my guts like an orca eating a seal.','24');
INSERT INTO `page_parts` (`id`,`name`,`filter_id`,`content`,`page_id`) VALUES ('43','body','Textile','The cat apparently ate something strange and suffered a bit of gastrointestinal disorder.  I have been waiting for this day for eleven years, ever since my tiny feline Christmas present began eating the box he came in.  I think it may have been a bit of strapping tape that finally got him, though, poor beast.  He had been working his way though a shipping container and must have ingested the acrylic adhesive that makes tape stick when he tore the container apart.  I remember something from Polymers 241 in college to the effect that acrylic adhesive administered topically or intramuscularly causes sarcomas in rats and mice, but I have no idea what sarcomas are; I was in the technology department, not biology.  Apparently, a sarcoma is a massive attack of vomiting, diarrhea, and dragging your furry little ass all over the Persian carpet I inherited from the back of a truck near my grandmother\'s house.  \r\n\r\n!http://bitchkittyracing.com/assets/145/172.jpg!\r\n\r\nThe cat was sick for two days, weak and mewling, hardly able to disembowel his mealtime buffalo. Having lived with the devil for eleven years, I was sure it was just something he ate which, no matter how toxic, would pass through his system and be gone.  This cat has never been seriously ill a day in his life but, like all cats, barfs and shits by the boat load depending on how offended my guests will be with which smell.  \r\n\r\nHe was sick this time, though, and doing the horrible thing that cats do when it hurts to go to the bathroom: avoiding the litter box.  The little bastard has never before peed on a piece of furniture but, last night when I got home from honky tonkin\', unabashedly and gleefully wasted, there was a wet spot in the middle of the couch.  As I knew he wasn\'t feeling well, I just cleaned it up.  No big deal. \r\n\r\nThe Pasha, being a longhair, also needed a bit of cleaning himself south of the equator.  I soaked a wet rag and gave him a whore\'s bath down there, petting him and cooing to him.  He seemed very grateful to be rid of the smell.  When I awoke the next morning, he stank again, so again I soaked his hindquarters.  A proper bath would have to wait for me to get off work that evening.\r\n\r\nI related the story of my sick cat to my coworkers with a slight feeling of glee.  Eleven years of hair balls, scratches, and bites was leading to a feeling of justifiable vengeance satisfied.  \"He\'ll be right as rain as soon as he gets it all out\" I told whomever\'d listen, as most people really don\'t give a damn about another\'s pets or kids.  There were some doubts about his prognosis, however, and feelings that I may be wrong about the seriousness of his condition.\r\n\r\nDead wrong, at least according to my coworkers.  He obviously had seven different types of flesh-eating cancer and would die a slow and gruesome death which would cost me thousands and thousands of dollars.  One woman related the story of her cat having the same symptoms, and how he had to be put down: \"It was terrible!  Poor Kitty was so sick and the vet said the only humane thing to do was to murder my baby and then they pulled out a turkey baster and jabbed it in and out of her brain and there was blood everywhere and the cat screamed and cried and I screamed and cried and I was all covered with blood and guts and brains and I cried and cried for days and I\'ll never love another human being again because I\'m dead inside FOREVER!\"\r\n\r\nObviously, if I did not immediately take The Pasha to the kittycat emergency room I was the worst human being who ever lived, right in between Pol Pot and Idi Amin.  If I did not put down my Martini, stop flirting with the new hot cocktail waitress, and leave my bar right now I was, in fact, killing my beast through neglect and should never be allowed near any living being again.\r\n\r\nFine.  \r\n\r\nAdmittedly, I was starting to worry a bit, but only because I didn\'t know if he\'d taste good if he died when he was this ill.  I keep an extra large stewpot around for the day that one of us finally succeeds in killing the other.  If I win, it\'s _Chat au Vin._  If he wins, I\'m sure I\'m _Homme Bourguignon,_ if he even bothers to cook me.  I imagine I\'ll just wake up one night to the sight of him thrashing around the bed, gulping my guts like an orca eating a seal.   \r\n\r\nHe was waiting for me at the front door like he always is, having heard my car blocks away.  As expected, he was completely recovered, just incredibly stinky.  If he had opposable thumbs I\'m sure he would have already given himself a nice soak in the tub, but claws and fangs only work on flesh.  It was bath time.\r\n\r\n!http://bitchkittyracing.com/assets/151/174.jpg!\r\n\r\nThough glad he was back to his old cantankerous self, I was a bit irritated at leaving both a drink and a cute brunette on a Friday night happy hour spree.  I went into the bedroom and took off my tie, searched around for fencing mask and leather gauntlets I wear on cat washing days.  The bed was incredibly mussed; I thought maybe I had forgotten to make it that morning.  I whipped back the sheets and there it was: the entire contents of my cat\'s bowels, along with length of strapping tape (I knew it!), in the middle of my bed.\r\n\r\nMy _new_ bed.  \r\n\r\nMy brand new silk-covered pillow-topped extra-luxury sleep system purchased at the expense of ever being able to retire, the only step I have ever taken in the direction of appearing civilized in the bedroom, with twelve pounds of liquid cat crap and three feet of plastic ribbon soaking into the middle of it.\r\n\r\nThen I remembered: there was a third item he\'d soiled over the years.  One of the seats out of my car.  I had pulled it out for racing (weight savings) and placed it in the living room.  He hopped right on it and curled up, fell asleep instantly.  My cat, right?  While I was away, the cat sitter said he never left that seat.  The minute I walked in the door two days later, he stood up in the seat and pissed all over it.  I tried to yank him off it, but he had his claws so far in I lifted both him and the seat.  This is a huge cat, mind you, a twenty-two pound Maine Coon, pissing while being swung around and around while hanging onto a car seat.  The smell never went away, no matter how many times I washed and soaked the seat with enzymatic cat piss remover.  I had to sell the car (a bit of advice: always buy a convertible with the top up).\r\n\r\nBut the bed, the bed . .  .\r\n\r\nLittle bastard.\r\n\r\nI went into the bathroom and taped the overflow drain of the tub shut, filled it all the way the very top.  I picked out a soap I know he hates, got on my safety gear and herded him into the bathroom with a tennis racket, one of our favorite games, right up there with Who\'s Going to Bleed the Most. \r\n\r\n_Boing!  Boing!  Boing!_\r\n\r\n*SPLASH!*\r\n\r\nIt was up to his ears.  After a moment\'s surprise, he popped his meaty paws on the edge of the tub and took a swipe at me, severing a tendon in my wrist. \r\n\r\nThen the little fucker started swimming.  _Swimming._  Then he ate the soap I was washing him with.  He totally ruined all my cat-torturingly good fun. \r\n\r\n!http://bitchkittyracing.com/assets/157/175.jpg!\r\n\r\nSo then he was clean and smelled good, but I was unsatisfied.  I thought about drying him in the microwave, but he was too big to fit so I just chased him around with a hair dryer.  \r\n\r\nBut now, now comes satisfaction.  I\'ve just oiled up the clippers and set them to the lowest height.  Usually he just gets a trim.  Today, today he gets a Mohawk.  Piss on my antique couch, will you?  Ruin my car seat, huh?  Crap in the middle of my bed, yeah?\r\n\r\n_Here, kitty kitty!_\r\n','24');
