INSERT INTO `page_parts` (`id`,`name`,`filter_id`,`content`,`page_id`) VALUES ('67','body','Textile','The Yamhill Valley contains portions of the Oregon wine country, but those are the boring bits.  Too much traffic, too many Winnebagos.  The rest is softly undulating fields of wheat, hidden creeks, and oaks.  Up in the hills there are limitless two-lane roads that go nowhere, sticky tarmac that feels like rubber under the tires.  Then down into a hidden valley named after the original homesteader back in 1850, long since dead, barn still being pulled into the earth by blackberries.  There are stretches of road that follow the original section lines; one mile straight, ninety-degree turn, one mile straight.  There are roads that follow the creeks, wending their way towards the river and the final journey to the sea, roads never planned by an engineer\'s geometry but merely paved-over buggy trails that flow according to the natural rhythm of the ground.  \r\n\r\n<txp:upm_image type=\"image\" image_id=\"47\" class=\"image\" show_title=\"no\" />\r\n\r\nI learned to drive on these roads, propped up behind the wheel on my grandfather\'s lap, too short to touch the pedals but still able to steer the Dodge Adventurer pickup, Grandpa patiently avoiding death with the occasional correction.  I learned to love speed on these roads, riding with my uncle back from logging sites in yet another Dodge pickup, a Power Wagon he called Snort, the one with the too-tall tires and overdrive, never frightened because Uncle Denny could do anything well.  \r\n\r\nI learned danger driving with my grandmother in the Dart coupe.  She spent her entire life in this valley and knew every pebble, every glacial erratic from riding her horse through here when she was a little girl.  The white vinyl bench seat had to be set to its most forward position for the controls to be within her reach, and that immaculate machine leapt and rolled through the roads, not always within the lines but with unerring determination, gravel often clattering through the wheel wells.  \r\n\r\nDriving through here with my mother was always a different experience.  She knew everything about the physical world and why it worked.  Every stop brought forth a lesson on the Lake Missoula deluge, why stars fell from the sky, where fool\'s gold came from, what these fossils were, or perhaps just a chorus of Hit Parade songs from World War II.  She grew up here too, spending lots of time in the ditches with my grandfather\'s Mercury back in the early Sixties, too much speed and not enough control.  She has the distinction of being the first in the Valley to have seat belts installed, just like in the stock cars of the day; she claimed she slid around on the bench too much to keep it on the road.  Seat belts and a pair of glasses made her a legendary midnight drag racer.  \r\n\r\nI had my first car out here when I was ten; a safety orange, Briggs and Stratton powered, 3  horse fury.  Pop the clutch and a fan belt drove the right rear wheel, hand throttle jammed so far forward that I broke the detent.  My first road course was behind the local grammar school, special permission being given by the superintendent of the district, our next-door neighbor.  Lap after lap with instruction from my father about line and control, stopwatch ticking as I learned that sliding is slow and wrecking is even slower.  Here I learned that it is impossible to outrun the police no matter how fast you are, my first high-speed chase ending with me trembling in my grandmother\'s arms as she charmed the cop out of sending me to prison for life.\r\n\r\nI learned to love my first road car out here, the sound of a Ford 302 burbling happily enough through a glass-packed exhaust until you stomped it and became crushed into the broken bench seat.  I worked on that car every chance I got, constantly tuning it up, changing out yet another bit that age had claimed under the supervision of my mother who knew everything there is to know about cars.  Next came the Fiat, an Italian mechanical nightmare that broke down every Thursday without fail, but nonetheless loved the gravel and dirt logging roads that abound here in the fir forests on the way to the coast.  Then the Giugiaro-penned Alfa Romeo, a beautiful car that looked totally out of place here, something in its angular bodywork completely missing the point of the water-carved scenery.  \r\n\r\nHere I destroyed the Subaru station wagon that was to be handed over to my ex-wife as part of our divorce agreement, completely ripping off the exhaust system and breaking the struts as I found solace imagining I was an international rally star.  Here I brought both my first and second Miatas, both cars an expression of absolute unfettered joy.  With the top down I explored every possible driving option within a hundred mile radius, able to hear birdsong clearly while bombing along at eighty-five miles per hour.  Here I sat in the passenger seat of my new Mini while my uncle once again broke 100 on a straightaway, still unafraid because Uncle Denny can still do anything well.\r\n\r\nOn this most recent trip I found new roads, even though this is my home.  Sometimes you have to give up your eyes to see things that have been in front of you your entire life.  Coming west out of another small farming village I wound the Mini up through third, fourth and fifth gears, topping 120 miles per hour before braking for a ninety-degree turn, then winding it out again on the straight.  Over and over, accelerate, brake, turn, accelerate, just letting the car run free.  The Mini is a purposeful machine, no matter how bright yellow it is, no matter what it looks like.  It doesn\'t care about anything but the moment, where it is right now in relation to where it\'s going.  It never looks back.\r\n\r\nI had a stupidly happy childhood.  I\'m having a stupidly happy adulthood.  The wisdom of my grandparents became totally real at 120 miles per hour; I had a complete perspective change.  No matter if I chose to look through the windshield, the side windows, or the rear view mirror, the car moved ahead.  Through the front, what was to come; through the side, the odd stop-motion photography that speed imparts to vision; in the tiny rearview mirror, gently rolling fields filled with newly sprouted Spring wheat, and nothing else.  At that speed, it\'s far better to look ahead and control your motion instant by instant.  Staring backwards is a sure way to wreck.  I finally get that, now.  \r\n\r\n\r\n<script src=\"http://www.google-analytics.com/urchin.js\" type=\"text/javascript\">\r\n</script>\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\">\r\n_uacct = \"UA-1192760-1\";\r\nurchinTracker();\r\n</script>','36');
