INSERT INTO `page_parts` (`id`,`name`,`filter_id`,`content`,`page_id`) VALUES ('526','body','Textile','Let me tell you something about Seattle: it rains here.  Its cold and dark and wet about nine months a year.  In a normal year, the rain starts November first.  September and October are crisp and clean, frosty mornings and crunchy leaves.  Then Halloween, the greatest holiday of them all arrives.  No matter what time you go to bed that night its starry and clear.  No matter what time you wake up the next morning chunks of rain are blowing almost horizontally into rotting vegetative matter.\r\n\r\nThe next time youll see the sun is July 5.  No matter what time you unpack your wet picnic gear at home after the fireworks and go to bed, its drizzly and cold.  No matter how early you wake up the next morning its a cloudless 70 degrees.  Summer is why we all live here.  There are no jobs, housing is almost totally unaffordable, the traffic is now officially worse than L.A.s, and every time you blink theres another God damned Starbucks in place of your favorite coffee shop.  But the Summers are nice.\r\n\r\nSeattle has only the two seasons.  Summer and Crap.  Did I mention the darkness during Crap?  There are rain clouds six miles deep obscuring the sun, which is fine because daylight only lasts for six hours anyway.  Which is fine because the clouds actually extend below sea level, even raining on the oysters, so youd never really know if it was light.  To the average observer it varies from dark gray to darker gray, from a cold moldy sponge on the back of the neck to clammy hands of Death choking the hope from lives, depending on the time of day.\r\n\r\nIf it ever got down to actually raining it might be fun, but it never really does.  In Fall we do have enough actual rain for brief periods to cause flooding.  The Tolt, the Skookumchuk, the Stillaguamish, and the Snohomish rivers will flood on cue every year about November 15.  Every field along the 1-5 corridor will be a muddy windswept lake for months (the farmers here actually dredge cow-depth drainage channels through their fields at the beginning of the rainy season every year).  After that, its pretty much like being a gynecologist for a goeduck; its cold, its wet, its slimy, you have no idea where the water is coming from and you dont really care.  You just want to get out of there.  For eight months its like this, always living on the inside of a cloud, rotting and slippery things underfoot, darker every day.\r\n\r\nOf course, all natives know that there is a possibility of snow at some point.  It wont stick, it hasnt for years, but its quite pleasant to look at in the late evening over a Baileys and cocoa.  Until the next morning.   Then the entire city shuts down and every citizen who ventures out is in mortal peril of some idiot from Minnesota thinking he knows how to drive in the snow.  All natives know that Western Washington has two modes: uphill or under water.  Its slippery enough going up the seven hills when its merely wet.  When frozen, most of them are actually closed.  In case  you missed that, dear reader, if it aint a hill its wet.  We all live on one of the seven hills or on the water (or perhaps in a place where a hill used to be, or in a place where there once was water.  Its very complicated).  Point being, native Seattleites (both of them) have very little practice driving in the snow and its very hilly.  The hills are closed when it snows, so we dont drive in the snow.  Period.  Any of us.  Ask anyone.  But those Midwestern madmen are out and showing off and routinely running into stationary objects, such as busses and fallen pedestrians, because they seem to have all missed the Uphill or Underwater? brochure we hand to all new residents to assist them a choosing a homesite.  \r\n\r\nSo, the terminally wet and never-ending darkness of the season of Crap is why Seattle is famous for coffee, beer, and industry.  We need to keep going.  We need to have lots of parties to keep our spirits up.  Grunge?  We were all very drunk, which is why you cant understand the lyrics.  Microsoft?  Of course we can all spend eighteen hours a day working in a cubicle; theres no point in going outside.  Boeing?  Get me the hell out of here!  The 600 million dollar monorail project which never got off the ground?  Damn Redhook, again.\r\n\r\nSo many people find Western Washington to be a wonderland of outdoor activities.  To them I pose the question: where are you from?  The natives know that its either cold, wet, and dark, or its sunny.  If its cold, wet, and dark were not going outside.  If its sunny were not going hiking.  We havent seen a bare shoulder in nine months and you want to take us into the woods?  Oh, no.  We know better.  Its uphill or under water.  Scrambling up mud or squishing in a swamp.  The direct opposite of fun.  You people can have it, and thank you for paying us the additional visitors tax we have on hotels and restaurants.  Skiing?  I think were all cold enough, thank you very much.\r\n\r\nI can still see the red lights demarking the tops of the buildings downtown, yet it rains and blows.  Its only October 1.  Somehow, Ive been robbed.  One month early this year I have to stock up on Viognier and Sancerre, Pinot Noir and Cabernet.  I have had to take especial pains to ensure that my liver will survive another dark season, buy sweaters early, and stock up on heavy ingredients for stew and cassoulet.  I dont even have a pumpkin yet!\r\n\r\nThis is the dating season in Seattle, for those of you who dont live here.  Every Spring we all become single with the sights and smells of exposed flesh.  Every Fall we all are ready to start dating seriously again, with thoughts of rainy Sundays spent in bed.  Why go outside?  Its nasty out!  Normally, if you havent picked a mate by Halloween, expect to spend Christmas alone.  This year, with global warming and a sixth El Nino, what will happen to us all?  We were unprepared!  Strange.  I digress.\r\n\r\nGet a pet.  Get more friends.  Start dating whether or not you are ready.  Its here, folks.  Early.  Crap.  \r\n\r\n<script src=\"http://www.google-analytics.com/urchin.js\" type=\"text/javascript\">\r\n</script>\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\">\r\n_uacct = \"UA-1192760-1\";\r\nurchinTracker();\r\n</script>','148');
