INSERT INTO `page_parts` (`id`,`name`,`filter_id`,`content`,`page_id`) VALUES ('713','body','Textile','I\'ll admit it: I\'m a huge James Bond fan, as he was written by Ian Fleming.   \"Casino Royale\" was the first book in the series, published in 1953 (Fleming wrote 19 more Bond stories until his death in 1964).  It is more serious than the others, darker, grittier, yet is also portrays Bond at his most human; in love.\r\n\r\nThe newly released DVD \"Casino Royale\" is the best 007 movie released to date.  It is an actual film noir suspense thriller, and a damned good example of the genre.  It explains itself as such in the opening frames, a B&W sequence which portrays Bond getting his 00 designation while describing the cold ruthlessness of the Bond we are about to watch in the movie. \r\n\r\nFrom the gorgeous and utterly appropriate opening title sequence through the unhappy ending, this is not the same James Bond we have come to know and love over the last 40 years.  Daniel Craig portrays James Bond as a person completely capable of killing other human beings as the situation warrants, rather than just an action hero who kills because it\'s in the script.  There is no actor in the franchise\'s career that has ever let the audience contemplate the screwed-up psychology that allows a man to kill another man.\r\n\r\nThere is also the love story between Bond and Vesper Lynd, portrayed by the French actress Eva Green.  While perhaps not entirely believable as a treasury executive, the attraction and subsequent relationship that develops between Bond and Lynd is completely believable, from the distaste at the beginning to the obsession at the end.  Vesper Lynd is equally as insane as James Bond, and it\'s beautiful to watch, brilliance on the part of the writers, actors, and directors.\r\n\r\nThere is one gripe I do have with the filmmakers though, and not just to show that I am not in the studio\'s pay: the scene where a ruffled and defeated James Bond voices no preference for shaking or stirring a Martini.  Yes, I understand that this is Bond\'s first mission and that this one plays a major part in his psychological development, or that the filmmakers are really trying to break the Bond movie mold by screaming to the world the Bond is only human, and who would care about a cocktail\'s preparation after such a beating?  However, you do not do that in the 007 franchise, you do not thumb your nose at 40 years of tradition.  It should have been left out, because an entire world of James Bond fans got shocked out of the James Bond world for a moment, breaking the suspension of disbelief.\r\n\r\nThe cars, however, show that the filmmakers respected tradition.  There is the 1964 Aston Martin DB5, referred to by it\'s complete title by Bond early in the film, that made it\'s first appearance in 1964\'s \"Goldfinger.\"  The new Bond car?  An Aston Martin DBS (a 2008 model).  Pure car porn.  There is also something else that is James Bond automotive tradition: Ford.  It\'s true.  In \"Thunderball\" (1966), Ford provided all the cars, and so there is the memorable scene of James Bond being visibly shaken by being Fiona Volpe\'s passenger in a Mustang at 100 mph (of course, anyone who\'s ever been in a 1965 Mustang at 100 mph understands Mr. Bond\'s apprehension).  In \"Casino Royale,\" Monsiuer Bond arrives at the hotel in a Ford Modeo, the most plebian of European passenger cars.  It is a nod to tradition however, and we must accept it, as Aston Martin is also in the Ford family of fine products, as are Land Rover and Jaguar, the other two makes in \"Casino Royal.\"  If the viewer can choke down this bit of too-much-in-your-face product placement, there is thankfully enough very little else (but there is some), much appreciated in any new Hollywood movie.\r\n\r\n\"Casino Royal\" runs almost two and a half hours, and I still started the disc back at the beginning when it was over.  This is not just a movie for Bond fans--it is a movie for movie fans.','213');
