INSERT INTO `page_parts` (`id`,`name`,`filter_id`,`content`,`page_id`) VALUES ('802','body','Markdown','It is an unfortunate fact of life that some people dont beat their children enough to avoid those children growing into car prowlers.  Car prowling is also not usually very highly punished because the value of the items stolen is not very high, and it is highly unlikely that the prowler will be caught at all.  These thieving little bastards can be defeated, though, and all it takes is a change in thinking.\r\n\r\nFirstly, understand that your car is not safe anywhere, not even in a locked garage filled with pit bulls and snipers.  Leaving your car unattended for any length of time is like walking out on your drunk girlfriend during a roofie-eating contest at a frat party.  You have no control over what happens when youre not there.  None.  With that in mind, remember that car prowlers are opportunists; do not give them the opportunity.\r\n\r\n**Avoiding Car Prowlers**\r\n\r\n*Your bad attitude does not protect your car.*\r\n\r\nSeriously, there is an entire legion of otherwise rational people out there who think the fact that they are bad-asses is some sort of crime prevention system.  Thats just foolish.  Your average car prowler is an opportunist and has no idea who you are, or that you own a gun, or that you would shoot him on sight if you caught him breaking into your vehicle.  In far less time than it takes you to pee, the car prowler has already smashed your window and gotten away.\r\n\r\n*Your unattended vehicle is not even safe for ten seconds.*\r\n\r\nTry this: time yourself breaking into an imaginary car with an imaginary rock.  Rock above your head, through the window, reach in, grab the backpack, run away.  How long did that take you? Seven seconds?  Four?  Youll never see him. \r\n\r\n*Your car is not a safe--dont leave ANYTHING in it.*\r\n \r\nNothing.  Not a single scrap of paper, a leaky pen, a hamburger wrapper or an old coffee cup.  If you must have blankets in the car, leave them in the trunk.  Do not leave CD folders in view, your iPod plugged in the stereo, the removable face plate on your stereo, etc.  The car needs to be clean enough so anyone peering through the window will see nothing to steal. It needs to be clean enough so there is nothing in it at all. Not even car prowlers will smash a window for absolutely no reason.  Dont give them a reason.\r\n\r\n*If you can leave your glovebox open without draining your battery, do so.*\r\n \r\nEmpty the glovebox first, of course.  Again, show the thieves that there is no reason to break into the car.  Try removing the lightbulb to avoid draining the battery(check with a qualified mechanic if you have doubts).  Keep registration and insurance papers someplace else, accessible but out of sight.  Your personal information is on those papers, and that can be stolen, too.\r\n\r\n*Dont get an aftermarket stereo.*\r\n\r\nAftermarket stereos sound better than the one that came with the car.  Its why we buy them. Its also why your window gets smashed and your dash gets ripped apart.  If you are buying a new car, get a sound system upgrade at that time (try having it thrown in as part of your bargaining).  If you must buy an aftermarket stereo, remember that the cash you just sent is basically sitting on your dash in plan view, so take the faceplate with you every time.\r\n\r\n*Do not EVER give your address to an aftermarket parts store!*\r\n\r\nThere are people in the installation bay who use that information to go to your house and steal back the pretty parts they just installed.  They know exactly whats in your car, and they know within fifty feet of where your car is probably going to be.  The mere information of your stereo brand and address can be bought and sold on the street.\r\n  \r\nDO NOT EVER give your address to ANY store for any reason.  They are flat-out lying if they say they need it for the return policy.  You have a receipt and thats all you need.  If they wont sell to you, go to someone who will.  This is the age of information theft, and all police departments frown out giving out personal information to complete strangers.\r\n\r\n*Park in well-lit and populated areas.*\r\n\r\nYour car is less likely to be broken into if there are witnesses.  Also, dont leave your car overnight next to a park or wooded area.  There are two examples in my neighborhood of high prowl areas: both are dark, rarely travelled, afford good getaway cover in parks, and also next to the freeway to cover up noise.\r\n\r\n*If you have a convertible...*\r\n\r\nAnyone who is even remotely serious about getting in your car can do so with something as simple as a sharpened spork, so be realistic. The cost of your soft top will probably outweigh the cost of any damage to your interior, sad but true, so the conventional wisdom usually states that you leave your car unlocked.  Check with your local law enforcement agency before making that decision.\r\n  \r\nSo thats a start, anyway.  Dont unintentionally make your car a target.  Dont leave anything in it of value, or leave anything in it at all.  Dont tell strangers whats in your car and where its likely to be parked.  Dont leave your car in an area where no one would see or notice a crime.  Dont be a target.\r\n\r\nAnd if you happen to catch a car prowler, please kick him once for me.','249');
