INSERT INTO `page_parts` (`id`,`name`,`filter_id`,`content`,`page_id`) VALUES ('828','body','Textile','I woke up in the middle of the night with a vision of my next daily driver.  After a year of wrenching soul searching, I know what I want: a 1999 BMW M3 Kombi.  \r\n\r\n_\"Did you just say you wanted a station wagon?\"_\r\n\r\nYes, yes I did.  \r\n\r\n_\"Really.  So tell me: how long have you been retarded?\"_\r\n\r\nNo, wait! Dude!  Seriously!  Think about it!  If a come-fuck-me red Ferrari blows your doors off, you think, \"Of course.  It\'s a Ferrari.\"  But if a navy blue family truckster leaps off the line in a fit of flaming smoke and fury, you\'re going to be confused.  Very, very confused.  You\'ll never win!  It\'s a sucker punch!  It\'s hysterical!  Super-duper go-fast with all the glorious utility of a Subaru wagon.  I wonder if I can make it all-wheel drive?\r\n\r\nOf course, oh my auto-geek brothers and sisters, as you already know, they never made a M3 wagon.  Isn\'t that great?!  Frankenstein never had it so good!\r\n\r\n_\"Why a 1999?\"_\r\n\r\n<img src = \"http://images.automotive.com/reviews/images/01bmw3series.jpg\">*{color:orange}_Cutiepants McGee!_*\r\n\r\nGood question!  Cheaper to buy, cheaper source materials, and in my mind the 1999 model year was one of the last years that BMW looked like, well, BMW.  Don\'t get me wrong, I am a huge Chris Bangle fan.  A Bangle BMW looks like nothing else on Earth, and the designs made the brand utterly distinct and have been aped the world over.  I have nothing but the highest respect for flame surfacing.  I just happen to find it repulsive. \r\n\r\n<p>  </p>\r\n \r\n\r\nSo I began my research this morning and, oh dear! look what I found:\r\n\r\n<r:asset name=\"2008_M3.jpg\">\r\n  <r:image size=\"display\" />\r\n  <r:caption />\r\n</r:asset>\r\n\r\nBMW has recently unveiled the design for the 2008 M3.  While certainly another go-fast masterpiece, I find that I must ask a rather silly and pointless question from a popular song by Amy Winehouse about the car\'s looks: what kind of fuckery is this?  Seriously, is it a Honda Civic EX Sedan or is it a Subaru Impreza?  I understand fully that the bump on the hood is undoubtedly to allow clearance for the naughty bits, but given that the car looks like a Japanese coupe, it looks like a a WRX reference.\r\n\r\nOkay, I\'m done.  Let\'s put dull design behind us and get back to the good parts of our magnificent obsession: revving the wee out of anything oily.  ','263');
INSERT INTO `page_parts` (`id`,`name`,`filter_id`,`content`,`page_id`) VALUES ('829','body','Textile','When I started tending bar fifteen years ago, a Martini order meant I would produce a shaken cocktail of one third dry vermouth and two thirds gin, pour it into a stemmed glass with a distinctive triangular profile, and garnish it with an olive.  It was also normal to hear the guest ask for a vodka Martini.\r\n\r\nIn modern times, a Martini is simply any cocktail served in a Martini glass.  Yes, the purists shout, grumble, flap their hands above their heads, gnash their teeth, and waddle about in small circles, but that is the situation today.  The Martini is almost certainly a fruit-flavored vodka muddled with more fruit and/or sweet herbs to cover up the taste of the alcohol, perhaps with sugar added.  Yes, you can hear my teeth gnashing, but being in the business means I accept as a viable reality whatever the guest wants.  \r\n\r\nBut I am not twenty-two.  When I order a Martini I expect the waitress to know that I mean only chilled vodka served up--and I do expect her to ask me whether I\'d prefer an olive or a twist--for that is the modern classic Martini: chilled vodka, no vermouth.  Being a purist, though, I often experiment with the vermouth portion of the cocktail, going back to nineteenth century basics with a sweet wine such as Sauternes or Moscato, or even using actual vermouth!  Gin also has it\'s lovely uses, bitter and savory being perhaps tastes acquired as an adult.  \r\n\r\nAbout a decade ago, I had a guy come into my bar and proclaim loudly that he was a New York City bartender. He was not only a bartender, but also a _bona fide_ prick (furthering my belief that, like cats, bartenders generally don\'t like other bartenders).  He did, however, teach me one of the greatest classic Martini variations, one that he claims Frank Sinatra ordered in his bar on numerous occasions.  Sinatra walks on water in my book, so I can only hope that this asshole was kind to him in his later years.\r\n\r\nh3. Martini Sinatra\r\n\r\nTo a shaker filled with ice, add:\r\nbq.  \r\n* one big shot of vermouth\r\n* dash bitters\r\n\r\nShake until frost forms on the outside of the shaker, then strain completely, discarding the mixture but retaining the vermouth-and-bitters-washed ice.  Over the coated ice, add:\r\nbq.  \r\n* two shots of ultra-premium vodka\r\n\r\nShake it again until a thin coating of frost appears on the outside of the metal shaker.  Strain into a Martini glass (obviously) and garnish with a lemon twist.  \r\n_Voila!_  Now now drink the night away while applying the term \"broad\" to every woman in the room.  Be sure to call the waitress \"baby.\"\r\n\r\nCheers!\r\n','264');
